Info

Input DESeq2 requires raw counts (not normalized, not scaled, and optional if been batch correctd). If input to DESeq is not batch corrected then we incorporate this into our modeling in DESeq2. Additionally, DESeq2 can estimate size factors (correct for differences between samples unrelated to experiment)…more on size factors

  • Normalizing for sequencing depth and RNA composition = sample specific size factors are estimated by median ratio of gene counts relative to geometric mean per gene thus allows for between sample comparisons.
  • to do this it creates a pseudo-reference sample per gene (using all samples) –> sample-gene wise count divided by pseudo-reference sample –> find sample median of that calculated value (NORMALIZATION FACTOR) –> go back to original sample-gene count divided by median
  • Note that DESeq models the normalization within model, therefore you don’t input normalized counts. We can extract the normalized count table if desired.

DESeq2 is based on a negative bionomial distribution, with the mean and variance linked by local regression. Negative bionomial models are good for modeling bulk RNA-seq count data, as it accounts for the overdispersion because an assumption of this model is that variance >= mean (overdispersion is present if we have heterogeneity, due to different Poison distributions).

Adjusted pvals have undergone Benjamini-Hochberg procedure for controlling the false discovery rate (FDR) in multiple testing experiments (thus gene,gene, etc)

DESeq2 implements a generalized linear model (GLM) and the user parameterizes the linear model.

Background

DESeq() details:

  • Function runs: 1) est of size factors, est of dispersions, negative binomial generalized linear model (GLM) fitting and wald stats

results() details (these are outlined in the object printout below too):

  • Adjusted pvals = BH corrected
  • User specified alpha val to use for adjusted pval thresholding for FDR analysis
  • Wald test to assess model fit (compared to likelihood ratio test). Wald test fits full model –> conducts tests for each gene to assess distance from 0 - using the full model coefficent(s) and their standard error(s) –> genes with coefficients significantly different than 0 will show this in their log2 fold change (and coefficient is reported as the log2fold change). - several studies have found that Wald-log test is better for RNA-seq data than others.

In RNA-seq data, larger variances grow with larger counts
